Martin Rypar

UCI Credit Card Dataset

This dataset contains information on default payments, demographic factors, credit data, history of payment, and bill statements of credit card clients in Taiwan from April 2005 to September 2005. The dataset was downloaded from https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/default-of-credit-card-clients-dataset and further informations are avaliable in enclosed P05_Dataset_Description.txt file.

Univariate Plots Section

Univariate Analysis

The dataset consists of 30 000 observations and 25 variables (age, sex, education, marriage, amount of given credit, repayment status 1-6 months back, amount of bill statement 1-6 months back, amount of previous payments 1-6 months back, default) where I am mainly interested in how is default variable (customer will not be able to pay his/her debts in next month) affected by other variables. Closer description can be found in enclosed P05_Description_Dataset.txt file.

First I recoded some of the categorical variables from their previous numerical coding (dummy variables) to more explicit and easy to read naming in order to have more clear plot descriptions.

Next I created two new variables: From amount of bill statements for last 6 months (BILL_AMT) were calculated weighted averages for each customer and similarly for amount of previous payments (PAY_AMT) for last 6 months.

Categorical Variables

  • ~22% is general proportion of defaulted customers within dataset
  • More than a half of the dataset consists of females
  • The most usual customer has university degree
  • More than a half of customers are single
  • The majority of people use revolving credit to pay debts

Quantitative Variables

  • Age as skewed distribution (long-tail) with majority of customers within 25-40 years old (older people do not use the credit cards and they prefer cash in most of the cases), median age 34 and proportion of defaulted customers remains between 0.2 and 0.3 with an exception of customers older than 70 years, where is huge gap and approx. only a half of people around 75 y.o. paid their debts.
  • LIMIT_BAL (amount of given credit) variable seems to have roughly skewed distribution
  • Average amount of bill statement (BILL_AMT) has the skewed distribution
  • The most common average of previous payments (PAY_AMT) is ~ 2000 NT dollars and again is of skewed distribution

Bivariate Plots Section

Bivariate Analysis

  • The proportion of defaulted customers per sex is slightly bigger within males
  • The proportion of defaulted customers per education seems to be highest within customers who completed only high school (but universtity graduates close enough)
  • The biggest proportion of defaults showed divorced customers
  • The most significant change in proportion of defaulted and non defaulted customers repeatedly occured between 1 month delay in payment and 2 months delay in payment - which draggs my attention
  • LIMIT_BAL (amount of given credit) variable has higher median within non defaulted customers
  • Average amount of bill statement (BILL_AMT) do not shows any significant differencies within people who default and those who do not
  • As expected average amount of previous payments (PAY_AMT) has higher median within people who do not default but with a higher variance
  • Females seem to be better debtors as they pay on time more often then males and the delay seems to be shorter as well for women

Multivariate Analysis

  • Observation that customers with higher initial deposit default in less cases than customers with lower deposit was strenghten

  • No clear evidence of that previous payments are dependent on age of customers

As the decision if the customer will default in next month is classification task with two possible outputs I tried to model this task with a logistic regression model (binary logistic regression). First I very simply divide dataset into two groups: training data - on which I will train the model and estimate its parameters and test data - on which I will test the accuracy of its predictions.

The majority of features are statistical significant at least at the 0.05 level. But some of the features are not, such as PAY_5m, PAY_6m, PAY_8m EDUCATIONhigh school, EDUCATIONuniversity, MARRIAGEmarried, MARRIAGEsingle, AGE.

According to absolute values of estimates of categorical features it seems that PAY_0 has strong impact on the output of model. The SEX feature increases value of function by 0.1486 for males which means that within males is slightly bigger chance of default, if the SEX is female then value of function do not change (this relationship is partially reflected in intercept). The SEX features is in conformity with my previous findings, on the other hand within the EDUCATION features it does not seem so. My findigs are that high school customers are more likely to default opposite to university customers whereas in the model it is contrarily. That might points out on that the model is not perfect.

Model confirm my findigns from previous parts such as: the higher initial deposit (LIMIT_BAL) the lower probability of default or males are more likely to default than females. The difference between the null deviance and the residual deviance shows how the model is doing against the null model (a model with only the intercept). The wider this gap, the better. Noticeable decrease of Residual Deviance caused adding PAY_0 (repayment status) feature into model and also LIMIT_BAL (initial deposit) feature.

Accuracy 0.8295 represents how precise is model when predicting default status on a new set of data. AUC (area under the curve) is another measure of accuracy, typical for classification tasks ranging from 0 to 1 (closer to 1 is better model). The ROC is a curve generated by plotting the true positive rate (TPR) against the false positive rate (FPR) at various threshold settings while the AUC is the area under the ROC curve. My model shows AUC 0.76 which is better than random guessing (AUC 0.5) but in general 0.76 is not very precise and at this kind of task is demanded much better precision thus the model could be significantly improved.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

The first plot shows how initial deposit(LIMIT_BAL) vary between default statuses, even though it is simple plot it shows valuable information that non defaulted customers have higher median of the deposit compared to customers who defaulted. And this information could be very quickly used by bank or other financial institution exposed to credit risk to for example analyze minimal level of initial deposit.

Plot Two

Description Two

I like this one because it nicely develops the finding that females are better in repaying their debts within this dataset. Where the proportion in groups like no consumption, revolving and paid are clearly bigger within females. Also trend seems to prompt that males have longer delays in repayment. This was observed also in different months (PAY_2, PAY_3, ).

Plot Three

Description Three

The third plot is very similar to second one, but brings very different insights and also offers one interesting thing. The plot shows proportion of defaulted customers per repayment status in last month, where is clear that customers with longer delay will default with much bigger probability. The interesting thing is that not only in the last month but even in previous months there is a big gap in proportion of defaults between one month dealay and two months delay. It is sign that if customer is not able to repay his/her debt until one month delay, the chances of repayment are dramatically dragged down.

Reflection

A lot of insights are very intuitive and could be expected, nevertheless thats the one of the reasons of doing such analysis - to confirm or disprove
the ideas, intuitions and expectations about the data. After few projects in Python a was quite comfortable with the language and thus the change of the environment was a bit painfull for me even though I like R and I like how easy is to do the nice plots in it. And also during analysis I struggled a little bit with continuity as I often leave the analysis and then return to it after few days and I felt like I lost the connection and I had to remind myself all the previous parts. On the other hand it has also positive side that it could bring some new points of view and ideas.

In future work I would like to develop better model by tuning the one I used - as my approach was quite simple (e.g.division of dataset could be done better as accuracy is dependent on the manual split to training and test set, prepare better features) or develop more advanced and more sophisticated classification models (neural networks, naive bayes or decision trees).
